title.narrative: Sub-Saharan Africa - Government Debt Issuance and Management. Government Debt & Infrastructure Finance - Kenya. Regional East Africa (Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, Burundi) - Government Debt Issuance and Management

description.narrative: Governance refers to the exercise of political, economic, and administrative authority to manage a country's affairs at all levels, including the capacity to formulate, implement, and enforce public policies and deliver services. Good governance includes modes of administrative authority that are inclusive, participatory, transparent, responsive, effective, and accountable. This includes support for strengthening legislatures and local governments; capacity-building; security sector reform; separation of powers through institutional checks and balances, between the executive and legislative branches, in particular; and avenues within government structures for accountability, oversight and meaningful public participation. In conflict or post-conflict environments, this includes support for reconstruction of state institutions and systems.

Support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy, most importantly financial intermediation – the efficient generation and allocation of savings to their most productive use.

This award strives to support the establishment of a sound private, well-functioning, equitable financial sector that fulfills critical roles in a market economy. More specifically, this includes Assist the National Treasury to enhance its debt issuance and management policy and operational activities, including the establishment of a Debt Management Office and building risk management analytical capacity.. Supports implementation of EAC-wide economic and financial market reforms and EAC convergence goals. Objective is to support the EAC Regional Financial Markets Development Plan and help each of the countries’ efforts to attain standards related to monetary and economic reform which have been earmarked as priority convergence criteria. The Regional Financial Markets Development Plan’s central focus is the harmonization of policy structures; standardizing fiscal, monetary and debt management frameworks; upgrading financial infrastructure, and building institutional capacity. A major EAC goal is increasing capital flows among the member countries. Assistance focuses on developing comprehensive debt management frameworks; identifying and removing barriers to securities market development; enhancing market activity so that local financial markets can serve as an efficient mechanism for the implementation of fiscal policy and monetary operations in host countries - all of which support economic growth and free capital flows..
